<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How does CSV to JSON conversion work?", answer: "The converter reads CSV text line by line, splitting each row by the chosen delimiter. If headers are enabled, the first row defines the keys for JSON objects, and each subsequent row becomes an object with those keys. Without headers, each row becomes a JSON array of values. The complete result is a JSON array containing all rows." },
  { question: "What delimiter should I use for my CSV file?", answer: "Comma is the most common CSV delimiter worldwide. However, in many European countries where the comma is used as a decimal separator, semicolons are standard. Tab-separated values (TSV) are common in data exports from spreadsheets and databases. Pipe-delimited files are used in some enterprise systems. Choose the delimiter that matches your source data." },
  { question: "What happens to quoted fields in CSV?", answer: "Fields enclosed in double quotes are handled according to CSV standards. Commas, newlines, and other special characters inside quoted fields are treated as part of the field value, not as delimiters. Double quotes within a quoted field are represented by two consecutive double quotes. This ensures that complex text data survives the conversion intact." },
  { question: "Should I use headers or not when converting?", answer: "Use headers when your CSV has descriptive column names in the first row, which is the most common format. The converter creates JSON objects with meaningful keys like {\"name\": \"John\", \"age\": \"30\"}. Disable headers when your CSV is purely numerical or when the first row contains data rather than column labels. Without headers, the output is an array of arrays." },
  { question: "Why are all JSON values strings after conversion?", answer: "CSV is a plain text format with no concept of data types. Every value in a CSV file is inherently a string. The converter preserves this faithfully. If you need typed values (numbers, booleans, null), you will need to post-process the JSON output. This approach prevents incorrect type assumptions, such as interpreting ZIP codes as numbers." }
]) %>

